Integration test suite for `ctx-scan`, exercising `walk_dir`, `check_run`, `update_run`, and `summarize` both hermetically (via in-memory fakes) and against the real filesystem in `std::env::temp_dir()`. It is the authoritative source of the on-disk contract for `.context/` artifacts and `.ctxignore`/`.gitignore` semantics — changes to sidecar layout, staleness rules, or ignore-file precedence must be reflected here or these tests fail.

Two in-memory fakes drive the hermetic half: `FakeFs` (a `BTreeMap<String,String>` implementing `ctx_summarize::fs::Fs`, with `with_source()` seeding `prompts/*` + `src/lib.rs`, and `prompts_only()` seeding just prompts) and `RecordingAgent` (implements `Agent`, records every `(system, user)` call, always returns `SUMMARY[{system}]`). These let tests assert exact call counts against `runner::MAX_TARGETS` scope-gate logic without touching disk or a real LLM.

Filesystem tests use `test_dir(label) -> PathBuf` (unique path under the OS tmpdir per test) and always `remove_dir_all` before and after — tests are not parallel-safe if two share a label, but each test uses a distinct one. Key filesystem-only invariants asserted here: `.ctxignore` seeds itself from `.gitignore` on first `walk_dir` contact and then fully decouples — later edits to `.gitignore` are never consulted again (`walk_seeds_ctxignore_from_gitignore_once_then_decouples`); `target/` is excluded by a built-in default even with no ignore file present; `.context/` and binary extensions (e.g. `.png`) are always excluded from walks.

`check_run`/`update_run` tests establish the staleness propagation contract: editing `src/main.rs` marks exactly that file plus ancestor dirs (`src`, root `""`) stale, and `update_run` on a single-file edit triggers exactly 3 agent calls (one leaf + one dir rollup + root rollup) — this exact count is asserted and will break if rollup fan-out changes. Deleting a source file causes `update_run` to report and delete the orphaned `.ctx` leaf (`report.orphan_leaves`), and the tree is fresh again afterward.

`prompts_path()` resolves prompts via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` join `../../prompts`, independent of test cwd, since filesystem tests use real prompt files while hermetic tests use fake `LEAF`/`ROLLUP` strings — the two prompt-loading paths (`runner::load_prompts` for hermetic, embedded prompt dir for real) must stay compatible with `StdFs`.